  "response": "Steam primarily produces **thermal energy (heat energy)** and **mechanical energy**.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Thermal Energy (Heat Energy):** This is the most direct energy produced. The steam itself is hot, and this heat can be used for various purposes.\n\n*   **Mechanical Energy:** Steam is used to drive turbines or engines, which convert the thermal energy into mechanical energy (the energy of motion). This mechanical energy can then be used to do work, such as generating electricity.\n\nIn some contexts, steam might also be indirectly involved in producing other forms of energy, such as:\n\n*   **Electrical Energy:** When steam drives a turbine connected to a generator, electrical energy is produced.\n\nTherefore, the main types of energy directly produced by steam are thermal energy and mechanical energy.\n",
